AN  - 1434860844
AB  - This research extends the concept of racial frames to study interracial violence. We contend that episodes characterized by such violence experience the phenomena of framing. More specifically, our research considers the subjective interpretations associated with the perceived causative factors of interracial violence. Our research suggests that the racial groups which participate in the violence attribute its roots in very different ways and that these assessments draw upon systemic racial frames. However, we also argue that media and official frames draw upon the white racial frame which legitimizes the subordination and oppression of African Americans. This frame has a positional hegemonic status, as is evidenced by the outcomes of interracial violence, which often systemically privilege whites. We explore these issues through a study of a riot in Tulsa, Oklahoma 1921. [PUBLICATION ABSTRACT]
