AN  - 762224781
AB  - Prior to Barack Obama declaring his intention to seek the presidency of the United States, Harry Reid, in apparent support of Obama's aspirations, claimed that Obama could win because he was a "light-skinned African American with no Negro dialect unless he wanted one" (Halperin & Heilemann, 2010:38). When this statement became public in the 2010 book Game Change, a political and media-driven firestorm erupted. Reid's words were debated in major news outlets, and his political friends and adversaries chimed in to either castigate or support him. Utilizing a thematic analysis of linguistic interpretations, this research explores the ways public language frames, obscures, and manipulates the realities of race and racism in this country. [PUBLICATION ABSTRACT]
